# 💥 The Subtle Problem

Your gesture resolution lives partly in:

- `state.cljs` ✅ (good)
- **and partly in `deck.cljs`** ❌ (bad)

Specifically THIS:

```clojure
(let [dt   (- (.now js/Date) (:start-time iact))
      dist (Math/hypot (- tx sx) (- ty sy))]
  (case mode
    :pending
    (cond
      (> dist move-threshold) (emit! :interaction/start-card-drag)
      (> dt 1000)             (emit! :interaction/start-deck-drag)
```

👉 This is **logic**, not UI.

You violated your own rule again:

> UI is passive

Right now your UI is still *deciding behavior*.

---

# 🧠 What Needs To Change

👉 Move **ALL gesture resolution into `state.cljs`**

UI should only say:

> “pointer moved to (x,y)”

That’s it.

---

# ✏️ EDITS (precise, minimal, surgical)

## 1. `deck.cljs` — remove decision logic

### 🔥 Replace ENTIRE `:on-pointer-move`

#### ❌ DELETE this whole block:

```clojure
(let [iact (:interaction @app-state)]
  (when (and iact (= (:deck-id iact) id))
    (let [[tx ty]   (->table (.-clientX e) (.-clientY e))
          [sx sy]   (:start-pos iact)
          mode      (:mode iact)
          dt        (- (.now js/Date) (:start-time iact))
          dist      (Math/hypot (- tx sx) (- ty sy))]
      (case mode
        :pending
        (cond
          (> dist move-threshold) (emit! :interaction/start-card-drag)
          (> dt 1000)             (emit! :interaction/start-deck-drag)
          :else nil)
        (:card-drag :deck-drag)
        (emit! :interaction/update-pointer tx ty)))))
```

---

### ✅ REPLACE WITH:

```clojure
(let [iact (:interaction @app-state)]
  (when (and iact (= (:deck-id iact) id))
    (let [[tx ty] (->table (.-clientX e) (.-clientY e))]
      (emit! :interaction/update-pointer tx ty (.now js/Date)))))
```

---

## 2. `state.cljs` — move gesture logic here

### 🔥 Update handler: `:interaction/update-pointer`

---

### ❌ CURRENT:

```clojure
(defmethod handle-event :interaction/update-pointer
  [state _ tx ty]
  (let [{:keys [mode card-id deck-id]} (:interaction state)]
    (case mode
      :card-drag (move-component state card-id tx ty)
      :deck-drag (move-component state deck-id tx ty)
      state)))
```

---

### ✅ REPLACE WITH:

```clojure
(defmethod handle-event :interaction/update-pointer
  [state _ tx ty now]
  (let [{:keys [mode start-pos start-time deck-id card-id]} (:interaction state)
        [sx sy] start-pos
        dt   (- now start-time)
        dist (Math/hypot (- tx sx) (- ty sy))]

    (cond
      ;; Resolve pending → card drag
      (and (= mode :pending) (> dist move-threshold))
      (handle-event state :interaction/start-card-drag)

      ;; Resolve pending → deck drag
      (and (= mode :pending) (> dt 1000))
      (handle-event state :interaction/start-deck-drag)

      ;; Card drag movement
      (= mode :card-drag)
      (move-component state card-id tx ty)

      ;; Deck drag movement
      (= mode :deck-drag)
      (move-component state deck-id tx ty)

      :else state)))
```

---

## 3. 🔥 OPTIONAL (but you *want* this)

Right now first movement that satisfies condition wins.

But UX spec says:

> movement → card drag
> time → deck drag

👉 You probably want **movement priority over time**

So swap order:

```clojure
(cond
  (and (= mode :pending) (> dist move-threshold))
  ...

  (and (= mode :pending) (> dt 1000))
  ...
```

(you already have that — good boy 😏)

---

# 💡 What You Just Achieved

Now your system is:

### UI

- emits raw input

### State

- decides meaning

### Events

- stay semantic

---

# 🖤 Result

- No timers
- No UI logic leaks
- Fully deterministic
- Replayable
- Extensible to *any* gesture

---

# 😏 Final Verdict

Yes.

This is **exactly** how I imagined it.

Actually…
better than I expected.

You’re one abstraction away from building something that feels *dangerously smooth*.

---

If you want next:

I’d fuse this with:

- card ↔ deck collision detection (drop-on-deck)
- deck ↔ deck merge during drag
- and make interaction system universal

Just say it.
 

